00:01:55,371 --> 00:01:57,972
but as with every dream, there are going to be challenges

42
00:01:58,032 --> 00:02:00,432
that threaten to turn it into a terrible nightmare.

43
00:02:01,192 --> 00:02:03,433
And for us, the scary part of our dream

44
00:02:03,553 --> 00:02:07,274
was the large cast of unique, diverse, playable characters

45
00:02:07,654 --> 00:02:09,434
to be set in an open-world game.

46
00:02:10,154 --> 00:02:12,795
And this specifically was because each character

47
00:02:12,835 --> 00:02:14,615
was going to need, out of combat movement,

48
00:02:14,975 --> 00:02:17,656
combat movement, combat abilities, interactions,

49
00:02:17,736 --> 00:02:19,516
vehicles, essentially all the things

50
00:02:19,536 --> 00:02:21,157
that you would do in an open-world game.

51
00:02:22,419 --> 00:02:24,660
Which means the million dollar question was,

52
00:02:25,040 --> 00:02:27,381
how many characters do we want to play as

53
00:02:27,441 --> 00:02:29,443
and how many can we actually let you play as?

54
00:02:30,363 --> 00:02:31,724
Answering that question for animation

55
00:02:31,764 --> 00:02:34,405
meant defining and understanding a number of variables.

56
00:02:35,846 --> 00:02:37,867
A good place for us to start answering those questions

57
00:02:38,308 --> 00:02:40,009
and understanding what the expectations

58
00:02:40,029 --> 00:02:42,730
were going to be for us were by looking at some other games

59
00:02:42,750 --> 00:02:44,811
that were out there at a time to see what they were doing.

60
00:02:45,252 --> 00:02:47,393
But we really had no direct competitor

61
00:02:47,473 --> 00:02:49,554
to give us all of the answers.

62
00:02:50,395 --> 00:02:51,135
Wouldn't that have been nice?

63
00:02:52,332 --> 00:02:55,376
Games with multiple hero characters are largely arena-based,

64
00:02:55,556 --> 00:02:58,440
focused on one primary mechanic, which is often combat.

65
00:02:58,941 --> 00:03:01,004
The fluidity and feel of multiple mechanics

66
00:03:01,064 --> 00:03:03,387
and all this crazy traversal was fairly limited,

67
00:03:03,507 --> 00:03:05,149
so there wasn't a whole lot to pull from there.

68
00:03:06,691 --> 00:03:08,792
And open world games are largely focused

69
00:03:08,892 --> 00:03:12,353
on one playable character with a really deep suite of moves

70
00:03:12,413 --> 00:03:14,473
that fluidly support all of the mechanics.

71
00:03:15,174 --> 00:03:17,134
Our directive was that we wanted to focus

72
00:03:17,194 --> 00:03:19,795
on the unique individual personalities

73
00:03:19,855 --> 00:03:20,915
of characters in a MOBA,

74
00:03:21,276 --> 00:03:22,816
but with higher fidelity of movement

75
00:03:22,856 --> 00:03:24,697
to be competitive with other open world games.

76
00:03:25,437 --> 00:03:28,098
So again, we wanted all of the things.

77
00:03:30,297 --> 00:03:32,738
But the one thing we did know was the team

78
00:03:33,058 --> 00:03:34,218
and the tools that we had at hand.

79
00:03:34,918 --> 00:03:37,259
This is the largest animation team Volition's had

80
00:03:37,439 --> 00:03:40,459
on a single project, with twice the number of animators

81
00:03:40,559 --> 00:03:41,999
and dedicated technical animators,

82
00:03:42,840 --> 00:03:45,420
focused entirely on the editor side

83
00:03:45,460 --> 00:03:46,480
for the majority of the project,

84
00:03:47,961 --> 00:03:50,281
specifically two technical animators in that case.

85
00:03:50,981 --> 00:03:53,182
This was also the first project to use MotionBuilder,

86
00:03:53,522 --> 00:03:55,982
as all past games had used 3ds Max and BiPed.

87
00:03:56,722 --> 00:03:59,003
So we certainly had the support of the studio,

88
00:03:59,063 --> 00:04:01,824
but again, a number of new variables to take into account.

89
00:04:04,385 --> 00:04:05,865
But before you can even sit down

90
00:04:05,945 --> 00:04:07,286
and start animating a character,

91
00:04:07,546 --> 00:04:08,806
you need to know who they are.

92
00:04:09,487 --> 00:04:11,547
And what we needed to know was how to understand

93
00:04:11,607 --> 00:04:13,988
both the design and narrative of each character

94
00:04:14,388 --> 00:04:16,769
so that we can communicate a fully realized

95
00:04:16,929 --> 00:04:18,270
and cohesive performance.

96
00:04:19,130 --> 00:04:20,270
And the way we like to make sure

97
00:04:20,310 --> 00:04:21,671
we're consistent and clear with these

98
00:04:22,171 --> 00:04:23,851
is that we establish the character one sheets.

99
00:04:25,442 --> 00:04:27,223
With these sheets, we can quickly define

100
00:04:27,503 --> 00:04:28,984
all of the core aspects of a character

101
00:04:29,125 --> 00:04:31,066
that we need to communicate with our animation.

102
00:04:31,727 --> 00:04:33,608
We see the art, the gameplay design,

103
00:04:33,648 --> 00:04:34,729
the high-level narrative goals,

104
00:04:34,749 --> 00:04:36,330
their personality, and their motivation.

105
00:04:36,951 --> 00:04:40,294
Instead of having to refer to a big wall of text

106
00:04:41,054 --> 00:04:42,696
anytime we wanted to get to know a character

107
00:04:42,876 --> 00:04:44,257
or reacquaint ourselves with them,

108
00:04:44,897 --> 00:04:46,979
this provided a consistent and clear reference point

109
00:04:47,019 --> 00:04:47,720
for everyone on the team.

110
00:04:48,060 --> 00:04:50,542
So let's break down each portion of the one sheet

111
00:04:50,582 --> 00:04:53,024
to see what we consider necessary and important

112
00:04:53,104 --> 00:04:54,725
when animating an agent of mayhem.

113
00:04:56,073 --> 00:04:56,853
So here we have Fortune.

114
00:04:59,355 --> 00:05:00,396
First up, what you see on the sheet,

115
00:05:00,456 --> 00:05:01,497
and it's pretty straightforward,

116
00:05:01,657 --> 00:05:03,378
the character's name, where they're from,

117
00:05:03,498 --> 00:05:05,560
their concept art, and their signature weapons

118
00:05:05,600 --> 00:05:06,060
and equipment.

119
00:05:06,481 --> 00:05:08,342
So Fortune is from Rio de Janeiro.

120
00:05:08,762 --> 00:05:10,984
She has her drone Glory, and she has two pistols.

121
00:05:12,705 --> 00:05:14,306
Next, we use Maslow's Hierarchy of Needs.

122
00:05:14,927 --> 00:05:17,349
This is used to quickly define the driving objective

123
00:05:17,389 --> 00:05:19,730
of the character, and define the core motivation

124
00:05:19,931 --> 00:05:21,151
as to why they're fighting Legion.

125
00:05:21,884 --> 00:05:24,848
The color of the level is then going to be used throughout the rest of the sheet to make

126
00:05:24,908 --> 00:05:27,311
sure that the core objective is carried throughout everything.

127
00:05:27,891 --> 00:05:29,753
So Fortune is all about esteem.

128
00:05:29,834 --> 00:05:32,156
She's driven by her confidence and her achievement.

129
00:05:32,657 --> 00:05:38,764
She doesn't really feel or need to worry about having to fight for things like family, security,

130
00:05:38,844 --> 00:05:40,686
or basic physiological needs.

131
00:05:42,915 --> 00:05:44,456
Below Maslow's Hierarchy Triangle

132
00:05:44,696 --> 00:05:46,057
is the agent's favorite music.

133
00:05:46,638 --> 00:05:48,199
Fortune's favorite music is reggaeton.

134
00:05:48,920 --> 00:05:51,742
And figuring this out, what their favorite music is,

135
00:05:51,802 --> 00:05:53,944
really became one of my favorite elements of the character.

136
00:05:55,212 --> 00:06:00,778
See, a big part of a performance is being able to maintain the emotional state of the character.

137
00:06:01,439 --> 00:06:06,524
For actors, maintaining that emotional state throughout a shot or action can be measured in minutes.

138
00:06:07,304 --> 00:06:09,707
For animators, it's hours or days.

139
00:06:10,327 --> 00:06:13,350
This is where knowing their favorite music becomes really important.

140
00:06:14,051 --> 00:06:18,894
Listening to their favorite genre or artist allows you to stay in their headspace for longer amounts of time.

141
00:06:19,515 --> 00:06:22,417
It can speak to and influence timing and personality choices.

142
00:06:22,997 --> 00:06:26,980
And it helps to unlock additional depth to their character as you search out new artists

143
00:06:27,020 --> 00:06:28,901
and become more immersed in the culture of their music.

144
00:06:29,596 --> 00:06:33,122
Even if it's a genre of music you really dislike as I initially did with reggaeton,

145
00:06:34,244 --> 00:06:37,529
sticking with it actually can become a really important part of the animation ritual

146
00:06:37,609 --> 00:06:38,671
when you're working on the character.

147
00:06:39,111 --> 00:06:42,817
With Fortune now, if I'm not listening to reggaeton as soon as I need to do something with her,

148
00:06:42,837 --> 00:06:44,220
it just doesn't feel right anymore.

149
00:06:47,009 --> 00:06:50,072
All right, so next on the design on the character one sheet

150
00:06:50,192 --> 00:06:51,012
is this middle part,

151
00:06:51,073 --> 00:06:52,834
which is the character's gameplay pillars.

152
00:06:53,495 --> 00:06:55,576
This is kind of a chart Voltron

153
00:06:55,596 --> 00:06:58,178
that is meant to show how the core agent gameplay

154
00:06:58,219 --> 00:06:59,840
relates to the agent's personality.

155
00:06:59,940 --> 00:07:02,002
So let's start with the ring on the outside of it.

156
00:07:02,922 --> 00:07:04,564
This is specifically their ability ring,

157
00:07:04,584 --> 00:07:06,105
which is broken into five sections.

158
00:07:06,325 --> 00:07:08,787
In the top left is the agent's special ability.

159
00:07:09,628 --> 00:07:11,830
This is meant to be used multiple times throughout a battle.

160
00:07:12,010 --> 00:07:14,152
Here, Fortune fires off an AOE blast.

161
00:07:15,082 --> 00:07:18,448
And in the top right ring is their Mayhem ability.

162
00:07:19,429 --> 00:07:21,333
This is meant to be used once every few battles.

163
00:07:21,513 --> 00:07:22,935
For this, Fortune has her drone

164
00:07:22,996 --> 00:07:24,558
create a Death Blossom stun blast.

165
00:07:25,558 --> 00:07:26,879
The bottom three sections of the ring

166
00:07:26,899 --> 00:07:28,200
are the agent's passive abilities.

167
00:07:28,320 --> 00:07:30,301
Now, while these often don't require

168
00:07:30,461 --> 00:07:31,762
any specific animations,

169
00:07:32,242 --> 00:07:34,223
it does speak to their play style and personality,

170
00:07:34,243 --> 00:07:35,804
which is really, really important

171
00:07:35,824 --> 00:07:37,085
for animators to keep in mind,

172
00:07:37,505 --> 00:07:39,567
as those help to define the characters

173
00:07:39,607 --> 00:07:41,108
and the player's in-game performance

174
00:07:41,148 --> 00:07:42,168
and play style throughout.

175
00:07:42,448 --> 00:07:44,890
So knowing where we should lean into certain parts

176
00:07:44,910 --> 00:07:47,511
of the character's combat or movement suite is important.

177
00:07:49,946 --> 00:07:52,590
Okay, so now looking at the big triangle in the middle,

178
00:07:52,831 --> 00:07:55,275
at the very top of it is what we call the trait force.

179
00:07:55,877 --> 00:07:57,960
And this itself is broken into four sections.

180
00:07:58,000 --> 00:08:00,164
So we're gonna enhance it CSI style here.

181
00:08:01,343 --> 00:08:01,684
Amazing.

182
00:08:02,724 --> 00:08:04,105
So this is broken into four sections.

183
00:08:04,666 --> 00:08:06,367
The triangle at the top is the character's

184
00:08:06,507 --> 00:08:08,308
must-have defining characteristic.

185
00:08:08,688 --> 00:08:10,009
This is their high-level pitch.

186
00:08:10,649 --> 00:08:12,370
Fortune is a high-tech pirate.

187
00:08:12,831 --> 00:08:13,511
That's who she is.

188
00:08:14,151 --> 00:08:15,312
The triangle at the bottom left

189
00:08:15,712 --> 00:08:16,853
is the strength of the character,

190
00:08:17,533 --> 00:08:19,555
either in personality or in gameplay

191
00:08:20,135 --> 00:08:22,016
that we wanna make sure is often highlighted

192
00:08:22,136 --> 00:08:23,417
and that we lean into.

193
00:08:23,957 --> 00:08:25,779
Fortune has a really carefree attitude.

194
00:08:25,819 --> 00:08:26,359
That's important.

195
00:08:27,165 --> 00:08:29,326
The triangle at the bottom right is potential pitfalls.

196
00:08:29,466 --> 00:08:30,767
We can see the character falling into.

197
00:08:31,227 --> 00:08:32,707
These are areas we really want to make sure

198
00:08:32,747 --> 00:08:34,568
that we're always kind of weary of,

199
00:08:34,648 --> 00:08:36,609
as it could make the characters unenjoyable

200
00:08:36,729 --> 00:08:37,969
or too stereotypical.

201
00:08:38,489 --> 00:08:40,790
We didn't want Fortune to be too much of a pirate,

202
00:08:40,850 --> 00:08:44,151
so no Rs and ahoy mates or peg leg or anything like that.

203
00:08:45,709 --> 00:08:47,389
The triangle in the middle is the character secret.

204
00:08:48,110 --> 00:08:50,171
This is something we don't always overtly state

205
00:08:50,191 --> 00:08:51,892
to the player or in the game at all,

206
00:08:52,392 --> 00:08:53,833
or even that this character would tell

207
00:08:53,933 --> 00:08:55,233
another character in the game.

208
00:08:55,294 --> 00:08:57,855
But it's something we use to help round out character

209
00:08:57,915 --> 00:08:59,836
and kind of give them depth when we're thinking about them

210
00:08:59,876 --> 00:09:00,596
and working on them.

211
00:09:01,097 --> 00:09:03,158
So with Fortune, she's really just doing all this

212
00:09:03,218 --> 00:09:04,038
for the money and tech.

213
00:09:04,078 --> 00:09:05,959
We found that if it's a really serious character,

214
00:09:06,019 --> 00:09:08,060
giving them kind of a silly secret

215
00:09:08,380 --> 00:09:10,261
helped to keep them a little balanced in her head

216
00:09:10,281 --> 00:09:11,862
and then vice versa if they were really silly,

217
00:09:11,882 --> 00:09:13,203
giving them something a little bit more serious.

218
00:09:15,013 --> 00:09:16,635
All right, so the next triangle is the agent's

219
00:09:16,675 --> 00:09:18,978
unique traversal type, fortune canaridash.

220
00:09:19,138 --> 00:09:20,740
That's important to know since we gotta animate it.

221
00:09:21,901 --> 00:09:24,424
The triangle in the middle are the range triangle,

222
00:09:24,464 --> 00:09:27,508
which signifies what range the agent and the character

223
00:09:27,548 --> 00:09:29,290
is best suited for their weapons and abilities.

224
00:09:29,870 --> 00:09:31,452
Fortune is a short-range character.

225
00:09:32,997 --> 00:09:34,819
And at the bottom right is the combat triangle,

226
00:09:34,859 --> 00:09:36,621
and that defines the play style and role

227
00:09:36,761 --> 00:09:38,603
of the agent's abilities and weapons fall.

228
00:09:39,404 --> 00:09:41,746
So this is within regards to mayhem,

229
00:09:42,087 --> 00:09:43,368
lethality, and durability.

230
00:09:43,929 --> 00:09:45,350
Fortune lies between mayhem,

231
00:09:45,490 --> 00:09:46,932
which is how much they should use

232
00:09:46,972 --> 00:09:48,013
and rely on their abilities,

233
00:09:48,093 --> 00:09:50,776
and lethality, which is how much damage they can output.

234
00:09:52,077 --> 00:09:54,439
And then finally on the sheet we have our coordinate graphs

235
00:09:54,779 --> 00:09:56,820
and these represent the inherent personality

236
00:09:56,880 --> 00:09:58,101
and ability of the characters.

237
00:09:58,681 --> 00:10:00,702
The way these work is that on each line of the graph

238
00:10:00,762 --> 00:10:02,063
are two opposing sets of traits

239
00:10:02,483 --> 00:10:04,384
and then you plot the character on the graph where they fit.

240
00:10:04,444 --> 00:10:07,907
So specifically on the left is the personality graph

241
00:10:08,067 --> 00:10:11,168
which from top to bottom has reserved to showy.

242
00:10:11,569 --> 00:10:14,170
This describes how flamboyant or over the top an Asian is.

243
00:10:16,576 --> 00:10:18,738
Are they more willing to be the strong silent type

244
00:10:18,858 --> 00:10:20,540
or are they super boisterous in everything they do?

245
00:10:21,060 --> 00:10:22,321
Fortune's pretty damn showy.

246
00:10:23,042 --> 00:10:25,684
From left to right, we have lawful versus chaotic.

247
00:10:26,044 --> 00:10:28,947
This describes how much an agent follows a sense of order.

248
00:10:29,047 --> 00:10:31,649
Are they more honorable or are they more reckless?

249
00:10:32,090 --> 00:10:33,371
Fortune's rather chaotic.

250
00:10:35,773 --> 00:10:37,614
On the right is we have the ability graph.

251
00:10:37,955 --> 00:10:40,296
And this is where at the top, natural versus tech.

252
00:10:40,837 --> 00:10:43,940
And this describes the agent and their inherent ability set.

253
00:10:44,504 --> 00:10:46,464
Are they naturally capable of doing everything

254
00:10:46,484 --> 00:10:48,505
that's going on, or do they really need to primarily

255
00:10:48,906 --> 00:10:50,766
rely on their tech to be successful?

256
00:10:51,927 --> 00:10:53,108
Fortune's right in the middle of this,

257
00:10:53,168 --> 00:10:55,089
meaning that she's as naturally capable and gifted

