00:12:36,232 --> 00:12:37,353
Okay, so once we had those,

302
00:12:37,533 --> 00:12:39,134
and we were able to have our characters

303
00:12:39,174 --> 00:12:40,135
more defined pretty easily.

304
00:12:40,786 --> 00:12:42,868
The other core part of the tone we really needed

305
00:12:42,908 --> 00:12:44,509
to understand to be able to communicate

306
00:12:44,589 --> 00:12:45,750
was the game's art style,

307
00:12:46,310 --> 00:12:48,392
which is defined on a high level for the game

308
00:12:48,892 --> 00:12:51,214
as theatrical, simplified, and vibrant.

309
00:12:51,795 --> 00:12:54,156
So our animation style needed to match that.

310
00:12:54,757 --> 00:12:57,239
And what that specifically boiled down to for animation

311
00:12:57,299 --> 00:13:00,181
was the idea of the ordinary versus the extraordinary.

312
00:13:02,123 --> 00:13:03,824
The ordinary would be things like walking,

313
00:13:04,084 --> 00:13:05,225
running, standing, turning.

314
00:13:05,746 --> 00:13:07,667
That could just be sort of standard mocap polish.

315
00:13:07,687 --> 00:13:08,548
We could get away with that.

316
00:13:09,950 --> 00:13:12,192
The extraordinary were gonna be things like jumping

317
00:13:12,232 --> 00:13:13,733
and dashing and special abilities.

318
00:13:14,033 --> 00:13:15,214
These were things that we knew we wanted

319
00:13:15,254 --> 00:13:17,175
to get a little bit more exaggerated with the style.

320
00:13:19,193 --> 00:13:21,314
And what's key about this is that this approach

321
00:13:21,434 --> 00:13:24,236
allows style to be used in a non-arbitrary way,

322
00:13:24,716 --> 00:13:26,136
attaching more pushed animations

323
00:13:26,196 --> 00:13:27,937
to clearly defined gameplay systems,

324
00:13:28,457 --> 00:13:31,178
which is necessary because stylized animations,

325
00:13:31,238 --> 00:13:32,699
just by their nature, take more time

326
00:13:32,719 --> 00:13:33,980
than standard mocap polish.

327
00:13:34,440 --> 00:13:37,621
So we needed to be smart in how and when we could embellish.

328
00:13:38,161 --> 00:13:39,542
And that intentionality, I believe,

329
00:13:39,602 --> 00:13:42,023
is what helps to create a unified experience

330
00:13:42,063 --> 00:13:43,483
and quality bar across the project.

331
00:13:45,458 --> 00:13:48,280
So with that in mind, our first style pillar is simplified,

332
00:13:48,800 --> 00:13:52,661
which we interpret on animation as a limited 2D style

333
00:13:52,741 --> 00:13:53,982
matching our overall aesthetic.

334
00:13:55,062 --> 00:13:56,883
That means the timing of extraordinary movements

335
00:13:56,903 --> 00:13:58,884
will be snappy, faster through the motion

336
00:13:58,944 --> 00:14:01,825
with longer held poses conveying the key moments

337
00:14:01,865 --> 00:14:02,765
of the movement or ability.

338
00:14:03,306 --> 00:14:06,227
This means really super simple lines of action

339
00:14:06,267 --> 00:14:07,627
during quick movements, sort of think of them

340
00:14:07,987 --> 00:14:10,609
like smear poses and less as individual storytelling poses

341
00:14:10,889 --> 00:14:11,569
throughout the actions.

342
00:14:12,563 --> 00:14:14,385
Now, when I say smear frames as reference,

343
00:14:14,526 --> 00:14:16,629
we aren't using any literal smear frames

344
00:14:16,689 --> 00:14:18,551
or shader tricks like a lot of places.

345
00:14:19,012 --> 00:14:20,854
What we're doing is we're thinking about the poses

346
00:14:21,035 --> 00:14:24,359
like smear frames, where we want to reduce the noise

347
00:14:24,440 --> 00:14:25,821
and complexity of the pose

348
00:14:25,882 --> 00:14:27,183
through those snappy transitions.

349
00:14:27,804 --> 00:14:29,905
For example, this is a front flip that was done early on

350
00:14:29,945 --> 00:14:32,146
that would show what it's like to be animated

351
00:14:32,186 --> 00:14:33,607
in more of a traditional style, right?

352
00:14:33,667 --> 00:14:36,288
On the way up, you have the arms and legs offset

353
00:14:36,348 --> 00:14:38,429
as they rise, leading into the spin,

354
00:14:38,449 --> 00:14:40,390
and then unrolling naturally as she descends.

355
00:14:40,811 --> 00:14:42,712
You know, nothing wrong with it, pretty straightforward.

356
00:14:44,292 --> 00:14:45,833
But when thinking of the poses

357
00:14:45,873 --> 00:14:48,074
in a simpler, more smear mindset,

358
00:14:48,935 --> 00:14:51,216
on the way up, we want the body to have the limbs brought in,

359
00:14:51,296 --> 00:14:53,197
creating a cleaner, singular line of action,

360
00:14:53,257 --> 00:14:55,958
removing any of that complexity and noise that's going on.

361
00:14:56,710 --> 00:15:00,191
Same getting them into the ball at the apex, it should happen a little bit quicker.

362
00:15:00,911 --> 00:15:04,031
Coming out of the ball, the character should, instead of unrolling naturally,

363
00:15:04,071 --> 00:15:06,832
they should snap into more of an iconic in-air pose.

364
00:15:07,332 --> 00:15:09,033
And then when they begin to stretch into the fall,

365
00:15:09,093 --> 00:15:11,893
again the character becomes more of that singular clean line of action.

366
00:15:12,293 --> 00:15:17,215
This is really the essence and intent of smears without having any tech that gives you smears.

367
00:15:19,377 --> 00:15:23,539
In regards to theatrical, by attaching our extraordinary actions to gameplay systems,

368
00:15:23,999 --> 00:15:28,641
the exaggeration of abilities and personality moments will help to draw focus towards the

369
00:15:28,681 --> 00:15:31,042
theatricality of the character just naturally.

370
00:15:32,643 --> 00:15:38,345
With Fortune's special ability, how her guns create a large ball of energy really isn't

371
00:15:38,385 --> 00:15:41,706
as important to us as making sure the action just fits her personality.

372
00:15:42,469 --> 00:15:47,039
wildly launching it forward while jumping with a double bounce land makes it feel like it makes

373
00:15:47,059 --> 00:15:50,727
sense even if it makes absolutely no sense how that ball of energy is coming out of those pistols.

374
00:15:53,526 --> 00:15:55,807
And then this leads just naturally into our vibrant pillar.

375
00:15:55,907 --> 00:15:58,008
And this means that the personality of the pose

376
00:15:58,068 --> 00:16:00,750
is just as important or even sometimes more important

377
00:16:00,770 --> 00:16:02,030
than the functionality of the pose.

378
00:16:02,731 --> 00:16:05,072
Instead of animating a traditional jump, for instance,

379
00:16:05,112 --> 00:16:07,633
which hits the proper mechanical poses along the way,

380
00:16:08,134 --> 00:16:09,935
we like to think of the characters more like Spider-Man.

381
00:16:10,695 --> 00:16:12,676
His poses when jumping through the air

382
00:16:12,736 --> 00:16:15,758
say far less about the mechanics of a traditional jump

383
00:16:15,798 --> 00:16:18,999
and more about that character specifically being in the air.

384
00:16:19,888 --> 00:16:22,429
By clearly defining ordinary versus extraordinary,

385
00:16:22,910 --> 00:16:24,751
we hope that we'll be able to strike both the bold

386
00:16:24,811 --> 00:16:27,872
and balance that we're trying to get with the style

387
00:16:28,373 --> 00:16:30,994
without feeling at odds with the mocap

388
00:16:31,394 --> 00:16:32,495
and hit that vibrant pillar.

389
00:16:34,236 --> 00:16:34,996
So with all that in mind,

390
00:16:35,076 --> 00:16:36,997
jumping was pretty important to nail down early on.

391
00:16:37,037 --> 00:16:39,959
And to me, I really feel like it's the definition

392
00:16:39,999 --> 00:16:41,320
of our extraordinary style

393
00:16:41,800 --> 00:16:43,621
and what we use to establish it, first thing.

394
00:16:45,204 --> 00:16:47,686
So this is a jump test I did really early on

395
00:16:47,726 --> 00:16:49,787
and pretty quickly to show how jumping in our game

396
00:16:49,807 --> 00:16:52,350
could look and feel a bit different than a traditional jump.

397
00:16:53,190 --> 00:16:55,172
Fortune was the first character I was gonna be working on

398
00:16:55,392 --> 00:16:57,394
and this model was one of our early test meshes.

399
00:16:58,075 --> 00:17:00,737
We knew we wanted multiple jumps with air dashing.

400
00:17:01,357 --> 00:17:03,119
Come on now, keep playing, you wanna play.

401
00:17:06,553 --> 00:17:07,814
with jumping, with air dashing,

402
00:17:07,954 --> 00:17:09,554
and when everyone on the team responded to it,

403
00:17:09,834 --> 00:17:10,815
it was like, all right, let's figure out

404
00:17:10,835 --> 00:17:12,815
how to break this down so the animators can match this

405
00:17:12,855 --> 00:17:15,416
and designers know what this would take to tweak in game.

406
00:17:19,437 --> 00:17:21,078
So, let's break down the very first jump.

407
00:17:21,578 --> 00:17:23,178
And this actually ended up being really close

408
00:17:23,198 --> 00:17:24,839
to Fortune's base jump in the final game.

409
00:17:25,679 --> 00:17:27,360
Again, notice the simple line of action

410
00:17:27,400 --> 00:17:28,580
on that first stretched pose.

411
00:17:28,680 --> 00:17:30,600
It's also worthwhile to note that she has

412
00:17:31,121 --> 00:17:34,121
zero anticipation on her jump on button and press.

413
00:17:35,657 --> 00:17:37,378
As she begins to blend to the top of the arc,

414
00:17:37,698 --> 00:17:39,279
she begins to hit her personality pose.

415
00:17:39,899 --> 00:17:42,120
Her crossed legs at the apex, of course,

416
00:17:42,160 --> 00:17:43,881
are not mechanically true pose for a jump,

417
00:17:44,342 --> 00:17:45,782
but they do help to start to speak

418
00:17:45,802 --> 00:17:47,503
to her more fun, freewheeling nature.

419
00:17:48,124 --> 00:17:49,685
Remember, we always want to be asking

420
00:17:49,725 --> 00:17:51,686
how does this character specifically look

421
00:17:51,766 --> 00:17:52,366
when they're in the air?

422
00:17:53,827 --> 00:17:55,328
As she squashes at the top of her jump,

423
00:17:55,448 --> 00:17:57,029
the core of the air pose is held,

424
00:17:57,689 --> 00:17:59,490
and it's really the follow-through of her limbs

425
00:17:59,550 --> 00:18:00,631
that keep the momentum alive.

426
00:18:02,299 --> 00:18:04,681
As Fortune begins to release into her descent,

427
00:18:05,042 --> 00:18:05,902
the legs drop first.

428
00:18:06,263 --> 00:18:07,864
This helps to give a sensation of gravity,

429
00:18:07,924 --> 00:18:10,106
pulling them down, but still allows for the feel

430
00:18:10,126 --> 00:18:11,528
of the hang time to be believable

431
00:18:11,588 --> 00:18:13,409
because the upper body and the core strength

432
00:18:13,429 --> 00:18:14,831
of the character stays the same in the air.

433
00:18:15,471 --> 00:18:17,053
Notice also that the arms sort of maintain

434
00:18:17,093 --> 00:18:19,295
a similar world space, even as they begin to rotate up

435
00:18:19,335 --> 00:18:22,498
to help further sell that held pose and sense of hang time.

436
00:18:24,014 --> 00:18:25,395
And then going into the fall proper,

437
00:18:25,915 --> 00:18:28,237
we have the reduced body to the clear line of action.

438
00:18:28,597 --> 00:18:30,798
We do have the arms bent to keep some semblance

439
00:18:30,918 --> 00:18:32,939
of control and strength within the character,

440
00:18:32,999 --> 00:18:36,201
but to help with the blend,

441
00:18:36,261 --> 00:18:37,642
we found that if we left them straight up,

442
00:18:37,782 --> 00:18:40,664
it would give some pretty ugly flashing and tripolation

443
00:18:40,704 --> 00:18:41,744
as they tried to settle,

444
00:18:41,784 --> 00:18:43,305
so it helped to bring them down a little.

445
00:18:45,247 --> 00:18:46,347
Which all this really just comes down

446
00:18:46,387 --> 00:18:48,128
to examining the spacing and timing

447
00:18:48,929 --> 00:18:51,110
is as the second important part beyond posing.

448
00:18:52,039 --> 00:18:54,660
So for reference, here's a pretty standard Muybridge jump,

449
00:18:54,900 --> 00:18:57,361
12 frames, shows you how many frames make up

450
00:18:57,441 --> 00:19:00,062
each part of the action from rising, hanging in the air,

451
00:19:00,082 --> 00:19:01,383
and then starting your descent.

452
00:19:02,603 --> 00:19:05,384
And here are the 27 frames for a fortunes jump in comparison.

453
00:19:05,885 --> 00:19:07,465
And you can start to see some numbers there,

454
00:19:07,805 --> 00:19:10,346
but better than numbers, right, is always just an image.

455
00:19:11,007 --> 00:19:12,268
So what we're really getting at is that

456
00:19:12,389 --> 00:19:14,251
instead of a standard parabolic curve,

457
00:19:14,331 --> 00:19:15,553
we want more of a plateau.

458
00:19:15,713 --> 00:19:18,496
A faster up, a longer hang time, and a heavier drop.

459
00:19:19,217 --> 00:19:21,440
And this timing helps to sell the style

460
00:19:21,460 --> 00:19:24,424
of having just an in-air pose instead of the standard jump,

461
00:19:24,484 --> 00:19:27,167
because posing means nothing if the

462
00:19:27,708 --> 00:19:29,130
physics of the world seems the same.

463
00:19:30,512 --> 00:19:32,374
And because of this, we also get the benefit

464
00:19:32,434 --> 00:19:33,716
of bringing the jumps into style,

465
00:19:34,096 --> 00:19:36,519
meaning that we can use the same for standing jump

466
00:19:36,879 --> 00:19:40,023
versus move jumps, because mechanical function

467
00:19:40,183 --> 00:19:42,045
isn't important, isn't what we're trying to convey here.

468
00:19:42,085 --> 00:19:43,307
It's the personality of the character.

469
00:19:43,687 --> 00:19:45,209
And because we're doing that, it can function

470
00:19:45,229 --> 00:19:47,312
for both standing and jump and running.

471
00:19:48,554 --> 00:19:50,955
So after implementing and tweaking this in game,

