00:21:23,595 --> 00:21:26,197
about twice the speed of the raw mocap

514
00:21:27,158 --> 00:21:30,081
with attention being paid to some spacing and timing.

515
00:21:32,143 --> 00:21:33,204
And here it is with a style pass.

516
00:21:34,195 --> 00:21:37,057
We adjust the timing to shave off another seven frames,

517
00:21:37,438 --> 00:21:39,879
but a lot of what this style is comes from the posing

518
00:21:39,939 --> 00:21:41,481
and timing before the point of contact.

519
00:21:41,501 --> 00:21:42,962
So let's break that down specifically.

520
00:21:44,563 --> 00:21:45,844
Again, like the jump, we're gonna start

521
00:21:45,864 --> 00:21:47,925
with that stretch pose, try and keep it super clean.

522
00:21:49,446 --> 00:21:52,048
The height of the in-air motion has been lifted overall

523
00:21:52,108 --> 00:21:53,529
to give it more of that hang time

524
00:21:53,569 --> 00:21:55,390
and anticipation to feel similar to the jump.

525
00:21:55,871 --> 00:21:56,731
And that leg, of course,

526
00:21:56,771 --> 00:21:58,613
will just be starting to drag immediately.

527
00:22:00,108 --> 00:22:03,552
The body has largely hit that held in air pose

528
00:22:03,572 --> 00:22:04,533
that's important to the character,

529
00:22:04,894 --> 00:22:06,976
even as that leg breaks that hip,

530
00:22:07,597 --> 00:22:09,079
entirely not worrying about it.

531
00:22:11,182 --> 00:22:13,164
And again, the body is really maintaining

532
00:22:13,284 --> 00:22:14,866
that overall sense of pose

533
00:22:15,547 --> 00:22:17,570
while we're still letting that leg drag around

534
00:22:17,610 --> 00:22:19,031
so that it helps to read more clearly.

535
00:22:20,315 --> 00:22:22,796
So when you watch it again, what you can hopefully feel

536
00:22:22,856 --> 00:22:24,556
more than see is that attention spent

537
00:22:24,616 --> 00:22:26,537
in that initial lead up to it,

538
00:22:27,037 --> 00:22:29,018
to make it feel more snappy and exciting overall.

539
00:22:29,978 --> 00:22:32,039
So it was pretty much then at this point

540
00:22:32,079 --> 00:22:33,459
in the style of conversation that,

541
00:22:33,960 --> 00:22:37,101
well how far can we actually push these things

542
00:22:37,181 --> 00:22:39,622
beyond timing and spacing and poses?

543
00:22:40,982 --> 00:22:42,142
Those conversations started to happen.

544
00:22:42,162 --> 00:22:43,283
And of course for animators that.

545
00:22:43,743 --> 00:22:45,524
usually comes to squash and stretch, right?

546
00:22:46,884 --> 00:22:49,265
And so we needed to make sure we defined that

547
00:22:49,305 --> 00:22:51,546
before people started going too crazy with it.

548
00:22:52,446 --> 00:22:54,087
Using MotionBuilder and not custom rigs,

549
00:22:54,447 --> 00:22:57,008
that inherently limited us to how much we could do.

550
00:22:57,428 --> 00:22:59,288
But again, with MoCap being a large part

551
00:22:59,308 --> 00:23:00,069
of our movement suite,

552
00:23:00,789 --> 00:23:02,069
it couldn't really be too over the top.

553
00:23:02,609 --> 00:23:04,090
So like our overall style,

554
00:23:04,130 --> 00:23:05,770
we needed to be rather purposeful

555
00:23:05,870 --> 00:23:07,311
and non-arbitrary in its use.

556
00:23:08,912 --> 00:23:10,193
So here's Fortune's dash left.

557
00:23:10,694 --> 00:23:12,976
There's some squash and stretch built into her spine,

558
00:23:13,057 --> 00:23:15,720
but it's more to carry the energy of the motion

559
00:23:15,800 --> 00:23:18,743
through the spine than to make it feel super snappy

560
00:23:18,843 --> 00:23:19,564
or over the top.

561
00:23:20,626 --> 00:23:22,567
You know, we really want you to sort of feel it

562
00:23:22,627 --> 00:23:25,888
more than see it and not have it instantly jump out at you.

563
00:23:26,949 --> 00:23:29,330
It isn't even also meant to be used on everything

564
00:23:29,450 --> 00:23:30,950
that needs to be brought into style,

565
00:23:31,070 --> 00:23:34,232
only when you need to sort of keep that pose or energy alive.

566
00:23:34,492 --> 00:23:36,773
It needs to serve the core functionality of the style.

567
00:23:37,733 --> 00:23:39,874
Posing and timing are really what are at the core.

568
00:23:39,894 --> 00:23:41,275
This just supports it.

569
00:23:44,216 --> 00:23:46,357
Okay, so we know more about the characters.

570
00:23:46,737 --> 00:23:48,178
We know more about the style of the game.

571
00:23:48,949 --> 00:23:50,950
we can now finally start to digging into

572
00:23:51,010 --> 00:23:53,532
what the overall quality of the animation is

573
00:23:53,612 --> 00:23:56,314
and start to find some more of those answers

574
00:23:56,374 --> 00:23:58,856
as to just how many characters we can support.

575
00:24:01,078 --> 00:24:03,080
So one last thing we really wanted to do

576
00:24:03,140 --> 00:24:04,721
before we got this was establish two rules.

577
00:24:04,901 --> 00:24:07,023
First, we agreed that out of combat

578
00:24:07,163 --> 00:24:09,965
needed to have higher quality visuals versus in combat.

579
00:24:10,586 --> 00:24:12,467
This was because the player character

580
00:24:12,647 --> 00:24:14,969
is really the focus of them out of combat.

581
00:24:14,989 --> 00:24:16,711
You're watching the character as you're playing with them.

582
00:24:16,771 --> 00:24:16,891
But.

583
00:24:17,691 --> 00:24:19,492
During combat, right, you're watching the reticle,

584
00:24:19,512 --> 00:24:21,133
the character is in focus to that.

585
00:24:21,253 --> 00:24:24,215
So we decided that was a pretty good balance to strike

586
00:24:24,275 --> 00:24:25,595
as to where to really spend our time.

587
00:24:26,276 --> 00:24:28,877
And then second was that that would,

588
00:24:29,777 --> 00:24:31,098
we wanted to start with on-ground movement

589
00:24:31,298 --> 00:24:33,199
because that's really something that's pretty common

590
00:24:33,439 --> 00:24:36,181
in every game and has a lot of expectations

591
00:24:36,221 --> 00:24:38,502
in regards to fluidity and responsiveness

592
00:24:38,542 --> 00:24:41,163
that we knew we needed to be able to deliver.

593
00:24:42,409 --> 00:24:44,570
So what we did was we started with the bare minimum

594
00:24:44,750 --> 00:24:46,932
of just a idle jog and blends

595
00:24:46,992 --> 00:24:48,393
to see how terrible it would look,

596
00:24:48,453 --> 00:24:50,795
and of course it looks pretty terrible.

597
00:24:51,275 --> 00:24:54,178
But it allowed us to identify the exact areas

598
00:24:54,218 --> 00:24:57,080
that annoyed us the most that we really wanted to target.

599
00:24:58,981 --> 00:25:00,122
And what that ended up leading to

600
00:25:00,222 --> 00:25:02,124
was four directional jog starts,

601
00:25:02,744 --> 00:25:06,507
two 180 jog turns, walk, jog, and sprint stops.

602
00:25:07,228 --> 00:25:09,390
We also have additive leans, additive head looks,

603
00:25:09,530 --> 00:25:10,470
additive torso looks.

604
00:25:11,342 --> 00:25:13,503
Establishing a standard like this

605
00:25:13,643 --> 00:25:15,705
allowed us to define gameplay metrics

606
00:25:16,105 --> 00:25:19,048
and markup on the assets for universal responsiveness

607
00:25:19,488 --> 00:25:22,310
to ensure turn rates at different parts of the animation

608
00:25:22,350 --> 00:25:23,651
could be leveraged by all characters.

609
00:25:23,791 --> 00:25:27,554
So for jog starts, every character needs to have turned

610
00:25:27,614 --> 00:25:28,835
by frame 10 to 12.

611
00:25:29,896 --> 00:25:33,279
And they need to be at full jog speed by frame 11 to 13.

612
00:25:33,959 --> 00:25:35,440
No matter the character's size,

613
00:25:35,660 --> 00:25:38,703
they needed to match this metric to match this system.

614
00:25:40,469 --> 00:25:42,051
which means selling weight and speed

615
00:25:42,251 --> 00:25:44,233
is entirely aesthetic like Hardtack here.

616
00:25:45,214 --> 00:25:46,295
After animating Fortune,

617
00:25:46,355 --> 00:25:48,437
one of the smallest and most agile characters in the game,

618
00:25:48,518 --> 00:25:50,359
Hardtack was my second character,

619
00:25:50,640 --> 00:25:51,541
which worked out really well

620
00:25:51,581 --> 00:25:53,423
because it allowed us to prove out

621
00:25:53,463 --> 00:25:55,245
that the metrics we defined with Fortune

622
00:25:55,285 --> 00:25:58,808
could still work for characters of any size.

623
00:25:59,658 --> 00:26:01,739
And what's really become one of my favorite things

624
00:26:01,799 --> 00:26:03,860
on the project is that during internal

625
00:26:03,920 --> 00:26:05,840
and external play tests, we usually always get

626
00:26:05,880 --> 00:26:07,201
some feedback from somebody that says,

627
00:26:07,581 --> 00:26:08,682
yeah, when I was running around the city,

628
00:26:08,702 --> 00:26:09,702
I always just switched to Fortune

629
00:26:09,722 --> 00:26:11,603
because she was faster and more agile than Hardtack.

630
00:26:12,063 --> 00:26:13,144
Even though under the hood, they are 100%

631
00:26:14,584 --> 00:26:17,225
at the exact same metric, no difference at all.

632
00:26:19,544 --> 00:26:20,925
Another example of meeting metrics,

633
00:26:21,005 --> 00:26:23,226
but selling the weight through animation is jumping.

634
00:26:24,047 --> 00:26:25,267
Unlike Fortune's base jump,

635
00:26:25,307 --> 00:26:26,968
which has no squash at the beginning,

636
00:26:27,008 --> 00:26:28,489
just that straight clear line of action,

637
00:26:28,949 --> 00:26:29,770
for larger characters,

638
00:26:29,870 --> 00:26:32,792
we do have about three frames of squash compression

639
00:26:32,812 --> 00:26:33,652
that happens at the beginning.

640
00:26:34,032 --> 00:26:36,354
And what that does is that covers the duration

641
00:26:36,374 --> 00:26:37,234
of the blend at the jump.

642
00:26:37,554 --> 00:26:39,275
And it helps them to feel just a little bit heavier

643
00:26:39,335 --> 00:26:40,356
on that first button press.

644
00:26:40,856 --> 00:26:43,278
They still hit the same height metric overall,

645
00:26:43,319 --> 00:26:45,020
they have the same overall time in air,

646
00:26:45,401 --> 00:26:47,723
but those three frames at the front, again,

647
00:26:47,803 --> 00:26:50,425
help to elicit that same feedback from playtesters

648
00:26:50,766 --> 00:26:53,428
that they do on ground movement that,

649
00:26:53,728 --> 00:26:55,150
well, if I'm jumping, I'm also gonna switch

650
00:26:55,190 --> 00:26:56,952
to one of the more agile characters.

651
00:26:56,992 --> 00:26:58,213
And again, it doesn't matter.

652
00:26:58,673 --> 00:27:00,795
They can get around the world with equal skill and ability.

653
00:27:03,143 --> 00:27:05,884
which really sort of led me to one of my favorite mindsets

654
00:27:06,324 --> 00:27:07,104
on the team, which was,

655
00:27:07,605 --> 00:27:09,325
let's solve it with universal systems,

656
00:27:09,745 --> 00:27:12,867
not tons of crazy unique assets if we can,

657
00:27:12,907 --> 00:27:14,687
because with multiple player characters,

658
00:27:14,847 --> 00:27:17,228
the number of unique assets we could support per suite

659
00:27:17,268 --> 00:27:18,529
was going to be limited.

660
00:27:19,149 --> 00:27:20,890
So the more common AAA approach

661
00:27:20,910 --> 00:27:23,431
of just throwing lots of animations into a unique suite

662
00:27:23,491 --> 00:27:26,032
for each system, it just wasn't gonna be possible for us.

663
00:27:26,672 --> 00:27:28,493
So the first big test of this

664
00:27:28,753 --> 00:27:31,454
was going to be out-of-combat stand turns.

665
00:27:32,154 --> 00:27:34,956
These are, of course, one of the deepest, darkest holes

666
00:27:34,996 --> 00:27:36,657
you can try and fill with animations

667
00:27:37,177 --> 00:27:37,998
for the rest of your life.

668
00:27:38,138 --> 00:27:40,859
Slow turns, fast turns, upper body versus lower body,

669
00:27:41,159 --> 00:27:42,140
keeping the feet locked down

670
00:27:42,180 --> 00:27:43,901
versus allowing slight translation.

671
00:27:44,301 --> 00:27:46,162
We just knew there was no way we could support

672
00:27:46,543 --> 00:27:48,904
a complex turning system for our characters.

673
00:27:49,484 --> 00:27:49,925
So we didn't.

674
00:27:50,845 --> 00:27:53,887
We, in fact, didn't make any animations for it at all.

675
00:27:54,908 --> 00:27:56,128
What we did is we used walk stops

676
00:27:56,789 --> 00:27:58,210
and we just let the system handle the rest.

677
00:27:59,178 --> 00:28:00,079
When you deflect the stick,

678
00:28:00,099 --> 00:28:01,039
you're getting a couple of frames

679
00:28:01,079 --> 00:28:02,419
of the additive head and torso look

680
00:28:02,459 --> 00:28:04,720
as well as that blend into the jog start.

681
00:28:05,360 --> 00:28:07,040
So the character has at least some facing

682
00:28:07,080 --> 00:28:08,481
of their body on stick deflection.

683
00:28:09,101 --> 00:28:10,521
And if we author the walk stop

684
00:28:10,561 --> 00:28:12,822
to have some additional foot shuffles back into place,

685
00:28:13,242 --> 00:28:15,362
what it does is it helps to sell the momentum of the turn.

686
00:28:16,122 --> 00:28:17,943
Sure, it's not gonna be as pretty as a turn system,

687
00:28:17,983 --> 00:28:21,023
of course, but it is free and it is responsive.

688
00:28:21,284 --> 00:28:22,604
And as a general rule,

689
00:28:23,024 --> 00:28:25,164
if there are a couple of ugly frames on input,

690
00:28:25,324 --> 00:28:27,665
as long as the follow through looks and feels good,

691
00:28:28,185 --> 00:28:29,085
people are gonna be okay with it.

692
00:28:31,889 --> 00:28:34,992
So vehicle entries are of course another huge investment

693
00:28:35,132 --> 00:28:35,833
with animations.

694
00:28:36,694 --> 00:28:39,437
Once you take into account multiple vehicle types

695
00:28:39,457 --> 00:28:40,579
that you need entries from,

696
00:28:40,899 --> 00:28:42,621
from different angles and different versions,

697
00:28:42,661 --> 00:28:45,064
and if they already have drivers or maybe passengers inside.

698
00:28:46,096 --> 00:28:48,917
What can be a giant suite and investment

699
00:28:48,937 --> 00:28:51,738
for even just one character across multiple characters

700
00:28:51,778 --> 00:28:52,939
would just be scope crushing.

701
00:28:53,459 --> 00:28:56,880
So when realistic functionality for us becomes too much,

702
00:28:57,561 --> 00:29:00,322
it's really time to lean into style and tone.

703
00:29:02,563 --> 00:29:04,884
And for this task specifically, we had two animators,

704
00:29:05,244 --> 00:29:07,545
Josh Behrens and Nick Kneebling light the way for us.

705
00:29:09,905 --> 00:29:12,209
Teleporting and swapping characters is a core part

706
00:29:12,289 --> 00:29:14,113
of the gameplay and tech that Mayhem uses.

707
00:29:14,714 --> 00:29:17,439
So using that as a cheat for vehicle entries made sense.

708
00:29:18,000 --> 00:29:19,763
Josh and Prototype had implemented it, but.

709
00:29:20,400 --> 00:29:24,462
It was really with the addition of Hollywood giving those finger guns as he cheeses to the camera

710
00:29:24,502 --> 00:29:30,045
that Nick added that extra bit of personality that really made the feature fully embrace the style and tone of the game.

711
00:29:30,606 --> 00:29:35,088
At which point, these have now sort of become more and more of signature animations for the characters

712
00:29:35,148 --> 00:29:40,231
as we kind of continue to one-up and show how they would cheese it up to the camera.

713
00:29:43,601 --> 00:29:44,982
The other place that we couldn't afford

714
00:29:45,002 --> 00:29:47,984
to add additional assets was turn fidelity while running.

715
00:29:48,664 --> 00:29:50,005
Designers and world builders, of course,

716
00:29:50,045 --> 00:29:52,627
wanted more narrow areas to move

717
00:29:52,707 --> 00:29:54,308
and controls needed to feel tight

718
00:29:54,368 --> 00:29:55,889
and responsive in those situations.

719
00:29:56,509 --> 00:29:58,130
And, of course, they still needed to look good

720
00:29:58,170 --> 00:30:00,131
when you're running down a wide open street.

721
00:30:00,652 --> 00:30:02,933
So instead of giving two entirely different suites

722
00:30:02,993 --> 00:30:05,535
for different situations or additional transitions

723
00:30:05,575 --> 00:30:07,656
based on different stick deflections or speeds,

724
00:30:08,517 --> 00:30:10,058
one of our senior animation programmers

725
00:30:10,118 --> 00:30:11,479
and a professional chicken wrangler,

726
00:30:12,099 --> 00:30:14,301
Isaac Veneer took a approach similar

727
00:30:14,341 --> 00:30:16,382
to out of combat versus in combat.

728
00:30:17,683 --> 00:30:19,385
See, when you want responsive controls,

729
00:30:19,405 --> 00:30:21,086
you're usually near ledges or doors,

730
00:30:21,146 --> 00:30:22,767
and you're more likely to be looking at.

731
00:30:23,580 --> 00:30:26,562
where the position of the character is and not at the character itself.

732
00:30:27,123 --> 00:30:32,107
But when you're in a wide open space and you want the character to look more fluid and weighty.

733
00:30:32,607 --> 00:30:37,231
So Isaac's solution was to toggle a near versus wide mode dynamically and in real time

734
00:30:37,271 --> 00:30:41,175
that adjusted the turn speeds based on very specific factors.

735
00:30:42,802 --> 00:30:44,103
If there was going to be a wall nearby,

736
00:30:44,283 --> 00:30:45,445
the character goes into near mode.

737
00:30:45,785 --> 00:30:49,330
If you want to turn the corner to go into the door,

738
00:30:49,630 --> 00:30:50,251
you would want it on.

739
00:30:50,671 --> 00:30:52,614
If you have a large thumbstick deflection while moving,

740
00:30:52,654 --> 00:30:53,375
it's gonna turn on,

741
00:30:53,755 --> 00:30:55,698
and when you start moving it again turns on.

742
00:30:56,298 --> 00:30:57,840
And it stays on for about one or two seconds

743
00:30:58,041 --> 00:30:58,822
in each instance,

744
00:30:59,623 --> 00:31:02,106
at which point it can switch back into wide mode.

745
00:31:03,179 --> 00:31:04,380
What this did was by adding it,

746
00:31:04,440 --> 00:31:06,041
it meant moving down narrow corridors,

747
00:31:06,101 --> 00:31:07,883
making tight turns and small adjustments

748
00:31:07,943 --> 00:31:10,305
to interact with an object were no longer an issue.

749
00:31:10,925 --> 00:31:12,667
And since the turn speeds governing this

750
00:31:12,927 --> 00:31:14,448
were being controlled by switching between

751
00:31:14,528 --> 00:31:16,229
different blend trees in the animation graph,

752
00:31:16,750 --> 00:31:19,112
it meant we could also then adjust our additive head

753
00:31:19,172 --> 00:31:20,973
and torso looks between each mode.

754
00:31:22,278 --> 00:31:23,899
So what this means is in wide mode,

755
00:31:24,219 --> 00:31:26,160
we have the body turn at a slower rate

756
00:31:27,141 --> 00:31:29,082
to look more weighty and fluid in game.

757
00:31:29,862 --> 00:31:32,243
So what we do then is we lead with the head

758
00:31:32,844 --> 00:31:33,644
and then the torso.

759
00:31:33,984 --> 00:31:35,605
And this gives the visual responsiveness

760
00:31:35,705 --> 00:31:39,747
to the player of their input of them looking

761
00:31:39,787 --> 00:31:42,809
as well as breaking up the overall order of operations

762
00:31:42,929 --> 00:31:44,249
on what's happening in the character

763
00:31:44,289 --> 00:31:45,870
so it doesn't just feel like you're turning a character

764
00:31:45,910 --> 00:31:46,330
on the stick.

765
00:31:47,171 --> 00:31:48,612
Essentially it's what we established

766
00:31:48,652 --> 00:31:50,713
in that original quality video.

767
00:31:51,489 --> 00:31:53,852
Notice the order of operations is the head

768
00:31:53,912 --> 00:31:55,934
and then the torso and then the full body turn

769
00:31:56,014 --> 00:31:56,554
while she runs.

770
00:31:58,516 --> 00:32:01,319
But in near mode, the body turns at a faster pace

771
00:32:01,459 --> 00:32:03,641
to allow for that positional responsiveness.

772
00:32:04,242 --> 00:32:06,704
We also wanted the head to turn fast

773
00:32:07,025 --> 00:32:08,346
to make sure that the character looks like

774
00:32:08,366 --> 00:32:10,048
they're aware of their quick directional heading.

775
00:32:10,669 --> 00:32:15,336
But then what we do is we have the torso counter rotate to simulate some drag and again break up

776
00:32:15,356 --> 00:32:20,403
that order of operations that's necessary to do. And at a certain point if running in a circle

777
00:32:20,704 --> 00:32:24,630
then we allow that torso to catch back up so that the head and torso are again leading the body.

778
00:32:25,914 --> 00:32:27,717
So this is what it looks like if I just turned it on

779
00:32:27,757 --> 00:32:28,658
even though I'm in a wide space.

780
00:32:29,399 --> 00:32:31,081
It of course looks twitchier than before

781
00:32:31,142 --> 00:32:32,864
and it's not as fluid or as appealing,

782
00:32:32,904 --> 00:32:34,867
but again, this is only triggered

783
00:32:35,187 --> 00:32:37,751
when the player cares about that need for twitch movement

784
00:32:37,831 --> 00:32:39,653
and fluidity and weight of the motion

785
00:32:39,693 --> 00:32:40,655
could actually get in the way.

786
00:32:41,556 --> 00:32:44,599
And you notice here as she runs in the circle

787
00:32:44,639 --> 00:32:46,561
that the torso drags behind the head and the body.

788
00:32:47,302 --> 00:32:49,285
Being to break up those order of operations

789
00:32:49,365 --> 00:32:51,347
is really key in making any of this stuff

790
00:32:51,707 --> 00:32:53,589
look in any way convincing or compelling

791
00:32:53,649 --> 00:32:56,012
without spending a crap ton of time on new assets.

792
00:32:58,618 --> 00:33:01,600
Another big animation asset sync is combat aim movements.

793
00:33:02,421 --> 00:33:04,302
Even though we decided not to focus as much

794
00:33:04,362 --> 00:33:07,104
on combat movement as we were going to out of combat,

795
00:33:07,745 --> 00:33:09,646
one area that we really wanted to address

796
00:33:09,766 --> 00:33:11,928
was those legs crashing through each other

797
00:33:11,988 --> 00:33:14,070
as they cross from front to back moving angles.

798
00:33:14,590 --> 00:33:17,012
But the traditional eight animations used

799
00:33:17,032 --> 00:33:19,554
before the studio per speed for this would

800
00:33:19,694 --> 00:33:21,775
really even add up across multiple characters.

801
00:33:23,256 --> 00:33:24,637
Enter at this point the mad genius

802
00:33:24,738 --> 00:33:27,179
of senior animator and cat lover, Clay Mathews.

803
00:33:27,540 --> 00:33:28,300
I don't know if he loves cats.

804
00:33:30,660 --> 00:33:32,383
The previous approaches used at the studio

805
00:33:32,583 --> 00:33:34,125
was to capture the four cardinal directions

806
00:33:34,746 --> 00:33:36,288
and then some diagonals as shown here

807
00:33:36,708 --> 00:33:38,150
to cover the transition of the character

808
00:33:38,170 --> 00:33:40,153
changing from that forward running gate

809
00:33:40,193 --> 00:33:41,074
to the backwards pedaling.

810
00:33:41,795 --> 00:33:43,878
And you would put them all into a single blend tree

811
00:33:43,978 --> 00:33:46,621
and blend them all smoothly as the thumbstick rolls around.

812
00:33:47,417 --> 00:33:49,979
Then in game, there was IK aim orientation

813
00:33:49,999 --> 00:33:52,502
with the upper body used to keep the character aiming

814
00:33:52,562 --> 00:33:53,763
at the straight ahead at the reticle.

815
00:33:54,383 --> 00:33:55,905
And while this certainly works,

816
00:33:56,165 --> 00:33:59,388
it still wasn't an ideal method for quality or even scope.

817
00:33:59,948 --> 00:34:02,690
And of course, not certainly at the release,

818
00:34:03,231 --> 00:34:05,133
in any way competitive with other approaches

819
00:34:05,213 --> 00:34:07,054
at other studios that use even more assets.

820
00:34:07,635 --> 00:34:08,816
So with the Matthew method,

821
00:34:09,336 --> 00:34:11,378
we can get away with only six animations

822
00:34:11,418 --> 00:34:14,521
which are all diagonals and requires no IK aiming

823
00:34:14,621 --> 00:34:15,281
to stay on target.

824
00:34:16,183 --> 00:34:17,885
The way this works is, instead of capturing

825
00:34:17,925 --> 00:34:20,789
the four cardinal directions, we capture back left

826
00:34:21,711 --> 00:34:23,413
and front right as single assets,

827
00:34:23,854 --> 00:34:25,957
and then the crossover angles of front and left,

828
00:34:27,018 --> 00:34:27,719
front left and back right.

829
00:34:28,480 --> 00:34:31,044
The three front moving animations are put in one blend tree

830
00:34:31,104 --> 00:34:32,225
and the three back in another,

831
00:34:32,325 --> 00:34:34,047
and then a state machine sits above those,

832
00:34:34,528 --> 00:34:36,250
switching between the two as they're driven

833
00:34:36,310 --> 00:34:37,672
by stick deflection of angle.

834
00:34:38,233 --> 00:34:40,315
There's a 10 degree overlap on those angles

835
00:34:40,375 --> 00:34:43,539
that switch between the forward and the back

836
00:34:43,579 --> 00:34:45,682
so that if someone's hanging out on that angle,

837
00:34:45,702 --> 00:34:47,103
you're not getting some ugly bounce, right?

838
00:34:47,900 --> 00:34:49,622
So we're gonna look at those animations

839
00:34:49,663 --> 00:34:51,405
before we actually see what this looks like in game

840
00:34:51,445 --> 00:34:53,347
so that people have a better idea of what we're doing.

841
00:34:54,088 --> 00:34:56,090
So this is what we consider a forward animation,

842
00:34:56,130 --> 00:34:58,974
which is, as you can see, 45 degrees forward right.

843
00:34:59,354 --> 00:35:00,636
The gate's pretty straightforward.

844
00:35:00,696 --> 00:35:04,400
The character is aiming at the camera relative,

845
00:35:04,440 --> 00:35:07,083
which is where the yellow arrow on the bottom represents.

846
00:35:09,079 --> 00:35:10,740
Here's what we would consider forward right,

847
00:35:11,160 --> 00:35:12,881
which is 135 degrees to the right.

848
00:35:13,382 --> 00:35:15,003
More than being a forward animation,

849
00:35:15,043 --> 00:35:16,264
this is really just a sidestep

850
00:35:16,544 --> 00:35:19,046
where the left leg crosses in front of the right leg.

851
00:35:21,407 --> 00:35:22,528
Here is the back right,

852
00:35:22,628 --> 00:35:24,550
which is again that 135 degree angle,

853
00:35:24,970 --> 00:35:27,012
but while also being a sidestep,

854
00:35:27,092 --> 00:35:28,673
it's the right leg crossing in front

855
00:35:28,693 --> 00:35:29,493
of the left leg this time.

856
00:35:30,922 --> 00:35:32,847
Here's a pretty standard back run,

857
00:35:32,987 --> 00:35:35,292
but this time it's at 135 degrees to the left

858
00:35:35,713 --> 00:35:37,457
and fairly straightforward back pedaling motion.

859
00:35:37,998 --> 00:35:38,980
I promise, even though it's not moving.

860
00:35:41,118 --> 00:35:43,819
Here's the back left, which is another sidestep,

861
00:35:44,059 --> 00:35:45,499
moving at 45 degrees left.

862
00:35:45,959 --> 00:35:47,680
And here it's the left leg crossing the right,

863
00:35:48,180 --> 00:35:50,300
and then the inverse for the forward left,

864
00:35:50,340 --> 00:35:52,521
which is right foot crosses in front of left.

865
00:35:53,001 --> 00:35:53,981
So here's what it looks like in game.

866
00:35:55,502 --> 00:35:56,602
Six animations for the jog,

867
00:35:56,622 --> 00:35:57,862
and then we'd have six more for the walk.

868
00:35:58,483 --> 00:36:01,023
And that gives us all of our combat movement for a character.

869
00:36:02,363 --> 00:36:04,184
Doing this takes a little bit of time getting used to

870
00:36:04,224 --> 00:36:06,625
when directing the mocap and authoring the animations,

871
00:36:06,665 --> 00:36:08,425
but once you wrap your head around it,

872
00:36:08,565 --> 00:36:11,726
you get everything you need for even less assets

873
00:36:11,746 --> 00:36:12,547
than what we had before.

874
00:36:12,987 --> 00:36:14,727
And it's entirely animation driven

875
00:36:14,907 --> 00:36:16,128
by the animation and the poses,

876
00:36:16,468 --> 00:36:18,888
so no IK tech is needed to keep them locked

877
00:36:18,948 --> 00:36:19,989
on that front reticle.

878
00:36:20,229 --> 00:36:21,309
We do have it for up and down,

879
00:36:21,369 --> 00:36:24,550
but again, most of the time it's right in that sweet spot

880
00:36:24,590 --> 00:36:25,070
and you're good to go.

881
00:36:27,514 --> 00:36:29,622
Okay, so since we're already talking about graphs,

882
00:36:29,642 --> 00:36:32,835
let's really just indulge our techie side completely.

883
00:36:33,541 --> 00:36:35,943
Beyond the evolving animation graph improvements

884
00:36:35,983 --> 00:36:38,625
and additions, the big gamble for us on this project

885
00:36:39,086 --> 00:36:41,348
was going to be procedural, as inspired by

886
00:36:41,428 --> 00:36:44,390
David Rosen's animation boot camp talk a few years ago.

887
00:36:44,431 --> 00:36:45,872
Check it out in the vault if you haven't seen it before.

888
00:36:46,352 --> 00:36:48,154
And what this meant specifically for us was

889
00:36:48,274 --> 00:36:51,597
IK modifiers, as created by another ace animation programmer

890
00:36:51,757 --> 00:36:54,519
and dude lookalike, Rob Ripka.

891
00:36:55,400 --> 00:36:57,622
And it really all started with Jumplands.

892
00:36:58,844 --> 00:37:00,927
Jumping is of course a big part of our game.

893
00:37:01,348 --> 00:37:03,892
And jump lands can account for nearly 40 animations

894
00:37:03,972 --> 00:37:04,513
per character.

895
00:37:04,973 --> 00:37:07,297
Jump land stand, jump land walk, jog, sprint.

896
00:37:07,697 --> 00:37:09,981
Aiming jump lands in all directions, across all speeds.

897
00:37:10,461 --> 00:37:12,745
For what is largely a functional animation,

898
00:37:12,865 --> 00:37:13,987
it can be a giant time sink.

899
00:37:15,088 --> 00:37:19,030
Looking around, some games might just play the jump land stand while moving to get the

900
00:37:19,050 --> 00:37:22,272
compression of the land and just blend out of it sooner, but that still wasn't going

901
00:37:22,292 --> 00:37:25,974
to meet with our overall visual quality needs by saying out of combat was what needed to

902
00:37:26,014 --> 00:37:26,475
look the best.

903
00:37:26,935 --> 00:37:29,316
So we decided to try our hand at procedural jump lands.

904
00:37:30,991 --> 00:37:32,292
So here's a jump land in our game

905
00:37:32,373 --> 00:37:33,874
when you're standing still with a procedural.

906
00:37:34,355 --> 00:37:36,097
Everything that the body and head are doing

907
00:37:36,738 --> 00:37:38,960
on the land is in fact procedural.

908
00:37:39,421 --> 00:37:40,442
We do animate the arms

909
00:37:41,042 --> 00:37:42,684
and they're exported as override animations.

910
00:37:43,405 --> 00:37:44,166
But under the hood,

911
00:37:44,546 --> 00:37:46,409
this is just the default idle animation

912
00:37:46,429 --> 00:37:48,991
that you're seeing with arms only playing.

913
00:37:51,095 --> 00:37:53,016
And here's that same jump land while you're moving.

914
00:37:53,656 --> 00:37:55,657
It uses the same arms override animation,

915
00:37:55,717 --> 00:37:56,797
but with an earlier blend out.

916
00:37:57,398 --> 00:37:59,238
But other than that, this is just the run animation

917
00:37:59,258 --> 00:38:00,159
that you're seeing when they land.

918
00:38:00,619 --> 00:38:03,820
And this overall saved us about 30 animations per character.

919
00:38:04,540 --> 00:38:07,001
Not to mention, it maintains full player control

920
00:38:07,141 --> 00:38:09,222
and velocity of the character while you're landing,

921
00:38:09,522 --> 00:38:12,123
which of course design and us game feel nuts

922
00:38:12,223 --> 00:38:13,263
just absolutely love.

923
00:38:15,324 --> 00:38:16,705
So how does this work?

924
00:38:17,721 --> 00:38:20,167
Well, I'm not Rob, I can't speak to the code underneath,

925
00:38:20,588 --> 00:38:22,893
but I can show what he exposed to us

926
00:38:22,953 --> 00:38:24,517
and how to adjust the knobs and dials

927
00:38:24,838 --> 00:38:26,421
so that we can manipulate what it does.

928
00:38:28,224 --> 00:38:30,125
It starts with defining a set of curves,

929
00:38:30,325 --> 00:38:31,565
or one curve specifically,

930
00:38:31,966 --> 00:38:33,146
and these are created in MotionBuilder.

931
00:38:33,727 --> 00:38:34,827
For the purpose of jump lands,

932
00:38:34,947 --> 00:38:37,769
we have ones defining how heavy we want that land to feel.

933
00:38:38,329 --> 00:38:40,631
The curve will drive what the bones will ultimately do.

934
00:38:41,171 --> 00:38:42,612
So in the light land at the top,

935
00:38:43,012 --> 00:38:44,953
the large value followed by a smaller value

936
00:38:44,993 --> 00:38:46,594
sort of represents a bit of a double bounce.

937
00:38:46,995 --> 00:38:48,636
For the heavy land, there's a large value

938
00:38:48,656 --> 00:38:50,357
that holds for a bit and then settles back

939
00:38:50,377 --> 00:38:51,918
without much of that double bounce,

940
00:38:51,958 --> 00:38:54,359
and this gives a land that holds a bit before rising up.

941
00:38:57,495 --> 00:38:59,396
Then what we do is we set a control parameter

942
00:38:59,416 --> 00:39:00,396
that we want to fire off.

943
00:39:00,536 --> 00:39:02,357
In this case, it's gonna be a bool,

944
00:39:02,377 --> 00:39:03,477
like round bool equals true.

945
00:39:04,538 --> 00:39:06,378
The function that I'm setting there

946
00:39:06,798 --> 00:39:07,879
is the motion builder file

947
00:39:08,059 --> 00:39:09,299
containing those previous curves,

948
00:39:09,339 --> 00:39:11,840
and then the function float track is the curve itself.

949
00:39:12,660 --> 00:39:13,401
And then you can see here,

950
00:39:13,421 --> 00:39:15,541
we can adjust some global values for it

951
00:39:15,561 --> 00:39:18,122
that are gonna be the length and output scale of the curve.

952
00:39:20,367 --> 00:39:23,469
Next is where we start adding in the specific operations on each bone.

953
00:39:24,389 --> 00:39:27,771
First we'll set the axis that we want to modify the bone on,

954
00:39:27,931 --> 00:39:30,232
then the bone name, as you can see there, the hips.

955
00:39:31,153 --> 00:39:34,135
Next up we can set a delay so that they don't all happen at the same time.

956
00:39:34,855 --> 00:39:38,077
Again, we can now set on a specific bone operation,

957
00:39:38,137 --> 00:39:40,719
the length and output scale, and then the offset.

958
00:39:40,819 --> 00:39:45,682
And the offset can be in translation, scale, or rotation.

959
00:39:46,002 --> 00:39:47,644
We can also set the space as you see here,

960
00:39:48,304 --> 00:39:51,166
which is model, which is T-pose,

961
00:39:51,686 --> 00:39:54,508
or bone, which is whatever pose they're in at the time.

962
00:39:55,231 --> 00:39:57,413
So instead of just walking through all this stuff,

963
00:39:57,433 --> 00:39:58,294
let's actually just make one.

964
00:39:59,215 --> 00:40:00,396
So this is what a jump looks like

965
00:40:00,436 --> 00:40:01,457
without any modifier on it.

966
00:40:01,898 --> 00:40:03,299
Like you see, it's just a stand

967
00:40:03,359 --> 00:40:04,861
with those wiggly arms going on,

968
00:40:05,241 --> 00:40:07,043
nothing too great feeling.

969
00:40:08,144 --> 00:40:10,707
Let's add that wide translation down on the hips,

970
00:40:10,807 --> 00:40:11,728
right on impact.

971
00:40:11,768 --> 00:40:12,669
And you can see already,

972
00:40:13,069 --> 00:40:14,931
all right, we're getting that curve

973
00:40:15,051 --> 00:40:16,212
as defined by the land heavy.

974
00:40:17,918 --> 00:40:21,221
Then we can add some rotation forward in X on the spine

975
00:40:21,481 --> 00:40:23,282
with a delay set in there to happen

976
00:40:23,662 --> 00:40:24,783
later than the transition.

977
00:40:24,843 --> 00:40:26,624
So we can break up that order of operations again

978
00:40:26,644 --> 00:40:27,285
that's really important.

979
00:40:27,945 --> 00:40:29,927
Having these live update is really a must

980
00:40:30,007 --> 00:40:31,508
as there's going to be a lot of iteration

981
00:40:31,548 --> 00:40:34,170
that needs to happen and being able to quickly compare

982
00:40:34,210 --> 00:40:36,071
and edit is really what's gonna be key

983
00:40:36,111 --> 00:40:36,891
in making this worthwhile.

984
00:40:38,374 --> 00:40:41,236
And about 15 operations later, we arrive at our jump lands.

985
00:40:42,097 --> 00:40:44,078
Obviously, creating these still takes some time

986
00:40:44,138 --> 00:40:45,499
and iteration to get it right.

987
00:40:45,859 --> 00:40:47,581
So the really big way that we win with these

988
00:40:47,661 --> 00:40:50,523
is that once we have a heavy and medium and light done,

989
00:40:50,943 --> 00:40:52,284
we can just add that to any character

990
00:40:52,324 --> 00:40:53,485
and their jump lands are complete.

991
00:40:53,865 --> 00:40:55,386
We just author some of that wiggly arms,

992
00:40:55,406 --> 00:40:56,927
which of course takes hardly any time at all,

993
00:40:57,468 --> 00:40:59,649
and character is jumping and landing

994
00:40:59,709 --> 00:41:01,791
and good to go right out of the box.

995
00:41:05,661 --> 00:41:07,241
The only time that we don't use that

996
00:41:07,621 --> 00:41:08,582
is during long fall lands.

997
00:41:09,102 --> 00:41:10,582
There's no fall damage for agents,

998
00:41:11,122 --> 00:41:12,243
and they're gonna be locked in place

999
00:41:12,283 --> 00:41:12,983
for a bit when they land,

1000
00:41:13,023 --> 00:41:14,183
so that means it's a perfect time

1001
00:41:14,203 --> 00:41:15,804
to add personality to the character.

1002
00:41:15,864 --> 00:41:18,564
So for Hollywood, who by his very namesake,

1003
00:41:19,004 --> 00:41:20,265
strikes a three-point landing,

1004
00:41:20,345 --> 00:41:22,185
because how do you land in a Hollywood movie?

1005
00:41:22,845 --> 00:41:23,465
Three-point landing.

1006
00:41:24,906 --> 00:41:26,126
I swear he's the only one that we do that with.

1007
00:41:27,466 --> 00:41:28,727
It was at this point, oh, sorry,

1008
00:41:29,287 --> 00:41:30,187
missed an important part.

1009
00:41:35,450 --> 00:41:37,511
All right, it was at this point then that Rob said,

1010
00:41:37,691 --> 00:41:39,231
wait, I'm not done, I can do more.

1011
00:41:40,032 --> 00:41:43,173
He made it that when you toggle sprint when jogging,

1012
00:41:43,773 --> 00:41:46,055
a modifier plays that compresses that character a bit

1013
00:41:46,355 --> 00:41:48,936
on button press to give that feeling of pushing off

1014
00:41:48,976 --> 00:41:50,957
and exerting some force into speeding up.

1015
00:41:51,557 --> 00:41:53,298
Since this is layered as procedural

1016
00:41:53,338 --> 00:41:54,798
on top of the sprint that's blended in,

1017
00:41:55,199 --> 00:41:56,819
again, it's not gonna change the velocity

1018
00:41:56,859 --> 00:41:58,180
or give you a hitch or anything like that.

1019
00:41:58,480 --> 00:41:59,701
It just makes it feel fluid

1020
00:41:59,721 --> 00:42:01,101
while still having that weight of like,

1021
00:42:01,141 --> 00:42:02,202
yeah, I kicked into sprint.

1022
00:42:04,170 --> 00:42:06,511
At which point then I fell madly in love with modifiers

1023
00:42:06,531 --> 00:42:08,512
and they quickly became the Frank's Red Hot Sauce

1024
00:42:08,552 --> 00:42:09,432
of animation tech.

1025
00:42:12,133 --> 00:42:13,854
First we added it to the out of combat

1026
00:42:13,894 --> 00:42:14,934
to combat transitions.

1027
00:42:15,215 --> 00:42:17,656
That blend to aim is only a couple of frames.

1028
00:42:17,736 --> 00:42:20,457
So the modifier gives us a nice bit of follow through

1029
00:42:20,477 --> 00:42:22,458
and overlap on the character

1030
00:42:22,498 --> 00:42:24,138
without delaying the combat responsiveness

1031
00:42:24,178 --> 00:42:26,459
of going directly into their aim suite.

1032
00:42:27,160 --> 00:42:29,401
We contrast this with those bespoke animations we make

1033
00:42:29,441 --> 00:42:30,742
when transitioning out of combat.

1034
00:42:31,242 --> 00:42:34,183
And again, what this does is it matches our overall decision

1035
00:42:34,203 --> 00:42:36,504
to focus on out of combat animation.

1036
00:42:36,605 --> 00:42:39,886
Showing how they transition from combat to out of combat

1037
00:42:39,926 --> 00:42:41,327
has sort of become a fun little way of adding

1038
00:42:41,627 --> 00:42:44,248
just that little bit of personality to draw the attention

1039
00:42:44,288 --> 00:42:46,630
and focus back onto the character after combat.

1040
00:42:49,678 --> 00:42:52,600
Then we use them as combat move starts and stops.

1041
00:42:53,160 --> 00:42:55,641
We have four cardinal starts and a single stop.

1042
00:42:56,061 --> 00:42:58,602
Since again, combat movement quickly just ramps up

1043
00:42:58,902 --> 00:43:00,382
to desired speed of the character.

1044
00:43:01,643 --> 00:43:03,704
What this does is this gives us a bit of a push off

1045
00:43:03,804 --> 00:43:06,244
like that jog to sprint transition does

1046
00:43:06,605 --> 00:43:09,186
and to settle like the out of combat to combat transition.

1047
00:43:09,926 --> 00:43:11,466
And then what's great about this is this is just

1048
00:43:11,626 --> 00:43:13,747
these five modifiers are shared across every character.

1049
00:43:14,507 --> 00:43:15,208
Everyone has it.

1050
00:43:15,468 --> 00:43:16,948
We don't have to make unique ones for them.

1051
00:43:17,068 --> 00:43:18,569
We could if we wanted to, but again.

1052
00:43:19,069 --> 00:43:20,991
combat isn't the focus where we spend a lot of time.

1053
00:43:22,973 --> 00:43:25,775
Weapon fires have also become a great place to use these.

1054
00:43:26,816 --> 00:43:28,197
And because as the library grows,

1055
00:43:28,257 --> 00:43:30,459
we can just add these to characters

1056
00:43:30,559 --> 00:43:32,321
or quickly dupe one and edit it

1057
00:43:32,381 --> 00:43:34,663
to get the unique fire per character.

1058
00:43:35,164 --> 00:43:37,526
What's also great about these is that they're easy to adjust

1059
00:43:37,726 --> 00:43:40,729
as the shot fire speeds are iterated on by design.

1060
00:43:40,789 --> 00:43:42,350
So instead of having to go back in

1061
00:43:42,390 --> 00:43:43,371
and adjust an animation,

1062
00:43:43,411 --> 00:43:45,493
we can just play with that global output scale or.

1063
00:43:45,869 --> 00:43:48,891
or anything like that, and now weapon fires are good to go.

1064
00:43:52,513 --> 00:43:54,214
This also gives us additive hit reactions,

1065
00:43:54,334 --> 00:43:56,676
which you can see here compared to the larger hit reactions

1066
00:43:56,696 --> 00:43:58,597
that actually do interrupt them, like there.

1067
00:44:00,198 --> 00:44:02,199
And by the nature of the modifiers being procedural,

1068
00:44:02,319 --> 00:44:05,061
it means they can work while the character is standing still,

1069
00:44:05,121 --> 00:44:07,382
moving, crouching, mandaling, jumping, whatever.

1070
00:44:07,502 --> 00:44:08,743
It doesn't matter what state they're in,

1071
00:44:08,763 --> 00:44:10,885
they're still gonna play the hit reaction.

1072
00:44:11,205 --> 00:44:13,466
And of course, then we can also use these on the player

1073
00:44:13,526 --> 00:44:14,987
without interrupting the player control.

1074
00:44:18,390 --> 00:44:21,293
Then we got the ability to scale bones with the modifiers.

1075
00:44:21,453 --> 00:44:23,835
So I added some squash and stretch to the agents

1076
00:44:23,855 --> 00:44:24,536
when they swap out.

1077
00:44:24,556 --> 00:44:26,478
You can see it easiest on hard tack where he kind of,

1078
00:44:26,758 --> 00:44:29,180
bloop, which was pretty fun.

1079
00:44:29,541 --> 00:44:30,502
And again, that way,

1080
00:44:31,102 --> 00:44:32,764
swapping no longer required an animation.

1081
00:44:32,804 --> 00:44:34,806
So as you're running through, swap to the character,

1082
00:44:34,866 --> 00:44:37,668
the next one comes in, fluid, responsive,

1083
00:44:37,949 --> 00:44:38,950
we're not interrupting anything.

1084
00:44:40,969 --> 00:44:42,554
At which point then we can get really silly

1085
00:44:42,635 --> 00:44:44,541
and just add procedural squash and stretch

1086
00:44:44,601 --> 00:44:46,547
to anything in the game that has a rig,

1087
00:44:47,370 --> 00:44:48,433
because why the hell not?

1088
00:44:52,194 --> 00:44:54,736
Okay, so finally, the last big hurdle

1089
00:44:54,796 --> 00:44:58,920
that we needed to solve was facial animation.

1090
00:44:59,600 --> 00:45:01,722
The tech solutions and expectations

1091
00:45:01,742 --> 00:45:04,284
that are out there with facial are, of course, incredible.

1092
00:45:04,704 --> 00:45:06,946
And while we definitely wanted higher quality animation

1093
00:45:06,986 --> 00:45:08,387
than previous games at the studio,

1094
00:45:08,828 --> 00:45:11,049
investing in facial capture or lots of custom

1095
00:45:11,310 --> 00:45:13,151
hand-keying animations just wasn't gonna work

1096
00:45:13,191 --> 00:45:13,992
on so many characters.

1097
00:45:14,052 --> 00:45:17,054
So again, it seemed here like leaning into style

1098
00:45:17,134 --> 00:45:18,776
was going to be what made the most sense.

1099
00:45:20,420 --> 00:45:22,801
What this meant specifically was focusing on strong,

1100
00:45:22,901 --> 00:45:25,562
emotive personality expressions like this iconic

1101
00:45:25,582 --> 00:45:27,502
Glen Keane expression she created for Tangled.

1102
00:45:28,343 --> 00:45:30,844
We would try to hit poses like those as much as we could

1103
00:45:30,864 --> 00:45:32,965
and then just sort of animate within those.

1104
00:45:34,554 --> 00:45:36,656
Specifically, what we would then do is,

1105
00:45:37,297 --> 00:45:39,379
this meant expression changes are what really

1106
00:45:39,399 --> 00:45:41,001
just take the most amount of time to sell, right?

1107
00:45:41,902 --> 00:45:43,844
On a physicality and emotional level,

1108
00:45:43,864 --> 00:45:45,946
those are hard and iterative.

1109
00:45:46,006 --> 00:45:47,688
So we just didn't have the bandwidth

1110
00:45:47,908 --> 00:45:49,850
or as much as we might have the desire for it,

1111
00:45:50,010 --> 00:45:51,232
not necessarily the need.

1112
00:45:52,033 --> 00:45:56,517
So it was best to just sort of make a scrunchie face like in the top

1113
00:45:56,597 --> 00:46:02,082
second left picture there to sell that contrast of changing from one emotion to another and

1114
00:46:02,182 --> 00:46:09,228
this was great because it also keeps it consistent with our extraordinary style of the strong personality poses carried by some of a

1115
00:46:09,568 --> 00:46:12,511
more clean smear mentality between them.

1116
00:46:15,094 --> 00:46:20,176
We were also cool with the fact that procedural mouths would be okay because people can deal

1117
00:46:20,196 --> 00:46:20,796
with that really.

1118
00:46:20,856 --> 00:46:26,359
It's the dead eyes and expressions that are going to make people go, that character doesn't

1119
00:46:26,399 --> 00:46:26,779
feel right.

1120
00:46:27,319 --> 00:46:32,201
If we can make sure that the eyes feel alive, the expression feels alive, then we'll be

1121
00:46:32,241 --> 00:46:34,402
okay with procedural mouth and most people probably will be too.

1122
00:46:35,922 --> 00:46:40,564
So what this did was it meant we were going to lean into the seven universal emotions.

1123
00:46:41,636 --> 00:46:46,639
This is anger, disgust, fear, happiness, sadness, surprise, and contempt.

1124
00:46:47,460 --> 00:46:49,941
Every human in the world has these things.

1125
00:46:50,682 --> 00:46:53,363
And while each expression has very specific traits

1126
00:46:53,403 --> 00:46:55,404
that you need for those to be able to read by everyone,

1127
00:46:56,585 --> 00:46:58,746
everyone sort of has their own unique version and take on it.

1128
00:47:00,050 --> 00:47:01,872
So this is what we did for each character as well.

1129
00:47:02,673 --> 00:47:04,275
And much like defining their music,

1130
00:47:04,455 --> 00:47:06,298
figuring out, taking the time to really figure out

1131
00:47:06,318 --> 00:47:07,459
which actors are characters,

1132
00:47:07,880 --> 00:47:10,523
parallel our characters' own personalities

1133
00:47:10,583 --> 00:47:13,527
meant we had another really great, quick touchstone

1134
00:47:13,567 --> 00:47:15,990
for finding and communicating performances

1135
00:47:16,050 --> 00:47:17,352
when working together on the team.

1136
00:47:19,540 --> 00:47:22,102
These expressions, along with the Anisoft Visemes,

1137
00:47:22,142 --> 00:47:23,643
were all outsourced to animators

1138
00:47:23,683 --> 00:47:24,723
with a past working in film.

1139
00:47:25,484 --> 00:47:27,765
The reference expression picture is what we gave them

1140
00:47:27,905 --> 00:47:28,846
as their initial direction,

1141
00:47:29,426 --> 00:47:31,688
and what they gave us back were these solid building blocks

1142
00:47:31,768 --> 00:47:34,729
that we were able to use by the rest of the team

1143
00:47:34,769 --> 00:47:36,290
that were handcrafted,

1144
00:47:36,711 --> 00:47:38,832
essentially animation-driven blend shapes,

1145
00:47:39,252 --> 00:47:40,473
as demoed here by a tool

1146
00:47:40,853 --> 00:47:42,954
written by our animation tech lead, Evan Cox.

1147
00:47:43,795 --> 00:47:46,177
And with these, what we can do is we can bring also

1148
00:47:46,257 --> 00:47:48,598
the Anisoft generated lip sync animation

1149
00:47:48,658 --> 00:47:51,240
into getFirstPass lip sync for anything that requires.

1150
00:47:51,780 --> 00:47:54,943
So very quickly, we can start to add facial animation.

1151
00:47:55,483 --> 00:47:58,325
So outside of a few specific animations shown here,

1152
00:47:58,345 --> 00:47:59,846
which are idle, fidgets, emotes,

1153
00:48:00,226 --> 00:48:01,828
mayhem ability, and front vehicle entry.

1154
00:48:02,868 --> 00:48:05,849
where the player can easily move around and look

1155
00:48:05,889 --> 00:48:08,290
and want to see that the face is matching the motion.

1156
00:48:09,070 --> 00:48:10,771
Everything else is authored with just no face.

1157
00:48:11,631 --> 00:48:14,912
And we let a default expression play underneath

1158
00:48:15,032 --> 00:48:16,653
so that when you're running and jumping

1159
00:48:16,693 --> 00:48:17,613
and all of that good stuff,

1160
00:48:17,893 --> 00:48:20,434
what you're seeing is that default expression under there.

1161
00:48:21,054 --> 00:48:22,695
Which meant it became really important

1162
00:48:22,835 --> 00:48:24,375
and we created an eighth pose,

1163
00:48:25,416 --> 00:48:27,837
which you can see here as demoed by our lead bad guy,

1164
00:48:28,197 --> 00:48:30,378
Dr. Babylon at the end, the personality pose.

1165
00:48:31,278 --> 00:48:33,360
And this would be the one that lives underneath.

1166
00:48:33,480 --> 00:48:35,222
It could be separate from the normal expressions

1167
00:48:35,502 --> 00:48:37,464
or even a variation of the expressions.

1168
00:48:38,244 --> 00:48:40,026
It was also then at this point that we decided,

1169
00:48:40,046 --> 00:48:41,768
well, if we're already making some changes to it,

1170
00:48:42,368 --> 00:48:44,390
it would be great if we could break up the sliders

1171
00:48:44,430 --> 00:48:47,533
to have the full expression, eyes only and mouth only.

1172
00:48:48,494 --> 00:48:52,637
And this was using Scott McCloud's approach to facial expressions as sort of inspiration,

1173
00:48:52,657 --> 00:48:57,320
in that being able to mix and match the eyes and mouths of different expressions and even

1174
00:48:57,360 --> 00:49:04,526
visemes would mean that we could quickly create new combined expressions to give extra depth

1175
00:49:04,706 --> 00:49:06,868
and variety to the characters pretty quickly.

1176
00:49:09,345 --> 00:49:12,626
So, with Fortune, getting her to reach

1177
00:49:12,666 --> 00:49:15,847
her full Rihanna potential took nearly no time at all.

1178
00:49:16,427 --> 00:49:18,487
With those static expressions now crafted

1179
00:49:18,567 --> 00:49:19,707
and implemented in the tool,

1180
00:49:20,708 --> 00:49:23,528
it seemed like being able to leverage them software side

1181
00:49:23,548 --> 00:49:25,189
was only really gonna be half a measure.

1182
00:49:25,569 --> 00:49:27,509
We would want to maybe see some of these expressions

1183
00:49:27,629 --> 00:49:28,570
in life, in game.

1184
00:49:29,811 --> 00:49:36,834
So we had our facial outsourcing gurus give us a single living expression to keep the face alive for each character.

1185
00:49:37,474 --> 00:49:44,077
Again, having them focus on it meant that it would meet a consistent higher quality than if we tried to rush it internally,

1186
00:49:44,457 --> 00:49:47,918
because balanced against gameplay needs, this just wasn't as important.

1187
00:49:51,408 --> 00:49:53,811
Then what we can do is we can copy multiple takes

1188
00:49:54,031 --> 00:49:56,113
of that animation in MotionBuilder

1189
00:49:56,514 --> 00:49:58,336
and drop each one of their unique expressions

1190
00:49:58,396 --> 00:50:00,678
on a layer over it, and now we have

1191
00:50:00,818 --> 00:50:02,640
all of those eight expressions alive

1192
00:50:02,800 --> 00:50:04,522
and at a fairly consistent quality level.

1193
00:50:06,785 --> 00:50:09,328
It's at that point that we have a system

1194
00:50:09,748 --> 00:50:12,111
to call all of those expressions in the game.

1195
00:50:12,882 --> 00:50:15,023
Is the agent gonna be happy to pick up an object?

1196
00:50:15,063 --> 00:50:16,084
Play their happy expression.

1197
00:50:16,544 --> 00:50:18,305
Are they angry that Legion is around?

1198
00:50:18,425 --> 00:50:19,665
Play that angry expression.

1199
00:50:19,725 --> 00:50:21,186
Or did they just witness something weird?

1200
00:50:21,846 --> 00:50:23,807
Drop that disgusted expression on them.

1201
00:50:24,908 --> 00:50:26,349
Fear even when they're at low health, right?

1202
00:50:26,989 --> 00:50:29,570
Facial animation really I feel like is something

1203
00:50:29,610 --> 00:50:32,011
where it's the definition of solving something

1204
00:50:32,091 --> 00:50:34,913
with a system and style, and then leveraging that

1205
00:50:35,073 --> 00:50:38,074
in as many places as possible across the game.

1206
00:50:41,318 --> 00:50:44,261
All right, so after defining the characters,

1207
00:50:44,621 --> 00:50:46,302
the style, the quality, and tech,

1208
00:50:46,843 --> 00:50:49,025
we're finally able at that point to extrapolate

1209
00:50:49,105 --> 00:50:50,967
just how many of these damn characters can we make.

1210
00:50:52,728 --> 00:50:54,130
What we did is we ended up with just shy

1211
00:50:54,150 --> 00:50:56,532
of 100 animations per player character.

1212
00:50:57,953 --> 00:51:00,676
And this is all of them, copied from character Excel doc,

1213
00:51:00,736 --> 00:51:03,438
because I know everyone in here loves to animate

1214
00:51:03,458 --> 00:51:04,820
in Excel sometimes, don't lie.

1215
00:51:07,126 --> 00:51:09,907
Specifically, something that we tracked and defined here

1216
00:51:09,927 --> 00:51:12,407
is which assets can be shared from one character to another.

1217
00:51:13,388 --> 00:51:15,208
And this is managed by having all of our character

1218
00:51:15,248 --> 00:51:16,908
animation sets live within a hierarchy.

1219
00:51:16,969 --> 00:51:19,169
So as long as one character is complete,

1220
00:51:19,529 --> 00:51:20,870
if everyone else is underneath them,

1221
00:51:21,610 --> 00:51:23,310
every character will inherit those animations,

1222
00:51:23,390 --> 00:51:26,071
allowing design to start testing that character right away,

1223
00:51:26,171 --> 00:51:28,431
and then we can just plug and play in animations as needed.

1224
00:51:28,812 --> 00:51:31,052
So with weapon holds, characters that are

1225
00:51:31,853 --> 00:51:33,255
Large male, underslung, cool.

1226
00:51:33,275 --> 00:51:34,517
If you want another large male underslung,

1227
00:51:34,697 --> 00:51:36,139
you've got complete access to one.

1228
00:51:36,780 --> 00:51:39,404
We'll just start plugging in stuff as it's necessary.

1229
00:51:40,586 --> 00:51:43,027
We also call out here which things will be animated

1230
00:51:43,087 --> 00:51:44,528
internally versus externally.

1231
00:51:45,048 --> 00:51:47,289
A lot of those ordinary classified movements are

1232
00:51:47,749 --> 00:51:50,371
and can be outsourced, including jog starts and turns.

1233
00:51:50,871 --> 00:51:53,832
Since the mocap really gives us a solid base and direction

1234
00:51:53,892 --> 00:51:56,073
and our metrics are so well defined and precise,

1235
00:51:56,613 --> 00:51:58,474
communicating our needs to external studios

1236
00:51:58,554 --> 00:51:59,615
is relatively straightforward,

1237
00:51:59,915 --> 00:52:01,396
as well as using the one sheets to say,

1238
00:52:01,456 --> 00:52:03,076
and this is their personality on top of it.

1239
00:52:03,934 --> 00:52:05,614
Sure, we still have to do a final polish pass

1240
00:52:05,714 --> 00:52:07,095
on all of those being implemented,

1241
00:52:07,435 --> 00:52:09,336
but what it does is it helps to make time

1242
00:52:09,376 --> 00:52:11,237
for us to focus early on on nailing

1243
00:52:11,257 --> 00:52:13,638
those extraordinary personality-driven animations

1244
00:52:13,898 --> 00:52:16,799
while still getting some runway laid

1245
00:52:16,879 --> 00:52:18,260
for the rest of their suite.

1246
00:52:19,980 --> 00:52:23,842
So after leveraging style, sharing, outsourcing, and tech,

1247
00:52:23,922 --> 00:52:25,163
100% unique characters are estimated

1248
00:52:25,443 --> 00:52:26,843
to take about 10 weeks internally

1249
00:52:26,923 --> 00:52:29,304
to create and implement all animations.

1250
00:52:30,005 --> 00:52:32,266
Shared weapons holds can save us five weeks.

1251
00:52:33,169 --> 00:52:34,790
Three weeks of polish and iteration

1252
00:52:34,850 --> 00:52:36,131
are then added to each character

1253
00:52:36,151 --> 00:52:39,093
so that we can react to any needed design changes

1254
00:52:39,153 --> 00:52:40,534
or iterations or playtest feedback.

1255
00:52:42,055 --> 00:52:43,756
And this is how many characters we have in total.

1256
00:52:44,397 --> 00:52:45,998
Beyond the 12 playable characters,

1257
00:52:46,078 --> 00:52:47,019
the four that we've shown today

1258
00:52:47,059 --> 00:52:48,560
and the remaining silhouettes that you can see,

1259
00:52:49,360 --> 00:52:52,002
we have 10 enemy troopers, seven unique NPC,

1260
00:52:52,403 --> 00:52:53,283
and multiple bosses.

1261
00:52:54,104 --> 00:52:56,246
And I cannot stress important enough

1262
00:52:57,226 --> 00:52:59,068
how great it's been to have this diversity

1263
00:52:59,188 --> 00:53:00,529
of all these characters on the team

1264
00:53:00,569 --> 00:53:02,550
by us being able to leverage a lot of these things.

1265
00:53:04,800 --> 00:53:07,202
Bringing the characters and the animation process

1266
00:53:07,262 --> 00:53:09,924
to life on this game has required for me

1267
00:53:09,984 --> 00:53:12,867
the perfect mix of art, design, and tech,

1268
00:53:13,347 --> 00:53:17,070
which really speaks to the heart of game animation

1269
00:53:17,131 --> 00:53:17,571
as I see it.

1270
00:53:18,312 --> 00:53:21,074
Taking the time to fully define the character's style,

1271
00:53:21,234 --> 00:53:23,416
quality, and tech up front has allowed us

1272
00:53:23,476 --> 00:53:25,598
to fully realize what I saw in my head

1273
00:53:25,658 --> 00:53:26,679
when I started on the game.

1274
00:53:27,440 --> 00:53:29,301
And moving forward, it's given us

1275
00:53:29,361 --> 00:53:30,802
an amazing foundation to build upon.

1276
00:53:31,708 --> 00:53:33,949
I hope you've all been inspired by our techniques,

1277
00:53:34,049 --> 00:53:36,610
and I can't wait for everyone to not only see more

